<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Landsbergis Urges Use of Partnership Rights </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS3101205794 Tallinn BNS in English 1830 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS3101205794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 31, BNS -- Under the presentiment of 
an international threat, Lithuania could exercise its 
partnership right to invite NATO consultants to Lithuania, said 
the leader of the Lithuanian parliament's rightist opposition. 
  Vytautas Landsbergis told reporters Monday [31 January] that 
consultants from NATO could have been invited to Lithuania 
during the signing of the Partnership for Peace program, to 
reflect on whether Lithuania is safe or not, confronted with 
Russia's current policy and certain statements of Belarus. The 
opposition leader said such a visit would enhance Lithuania's 
security. 
  Landsbergis said Lithuanian President Algirdas Brazauskas' 
speeches in the West were very cautious and expressed a position 
on "joint movement" that is soothing to Russia. He said the 
president's thoughts about a security zone from Vancouver to 
Vladivostok "resembles explanations by the Russian foreign 
minister that Partnership for Peace is a Russian, not an 
American idea." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

