<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visa Requirements, Border Crossings Discussed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0102163194 Tallinn BNS in English 1433 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0102163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Feb 01, BNS -- A group of Lithuanian 
experts dealing with visa and transit problems left for Minsk 
Tuesday [1 February], to discuss the introduction of visa 
requirements and the opening of new border crossings with 
Belarussian officials. 
  Virgilijus Bulovas, head of the group, said the two-day 
talks 
in the Belarusian capital will be mainly devoted to visa 
requirements for the CIS that will come into effect March 1. 
  Bulovas said he intends to hold several "semi-official" 
meetings in the Belarusian parliament and the Foreign Ministry. 
State border delimitation and the problem of the Adutiskis 
railroad station may be touched upon during these meetings, he 
said. 
  As previously reported, Lithuanian and Belarusian premiers 
signed an agreement last September saying that the Adutiskis 
station belongs to Lithuania, but some Belarussian lawmakers 
recently began to question the lawfulness of the decision and 
demand to revoke it. 
  Kazys Bobelis, chairman of the Lithuanian parliament's 
Foreign Affairs Committee, said it is necessary to determine 
border between Lithuania and Belarus as soon as possible and to 
start developing neighborly and trade relations. 
  Commenting on the replacement of the Belarusian head of 
state, Bobelis told Lithuanian radio Tuesday that a victory was 
won by politicians who advocate closer relations with Russia and 
whose policy is most likely to differ from that of the previous 
leadership of the parliament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

