<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Initiative To End Fighting in Karabakh Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101141694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1303 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3101141694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Georgiy Shmelyov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 31 TASS -- Russia has put forward a 
new initiative suggesting to completely cease fire in 
Nagorno-Karabakh, beginning from February 1, 1994, for a minimum 
period of two-three weeks. 
  The Russian proposal to this effect was conveyed several 
days 
ago by a special representative of the Russian president, 
Vladimir Kazimirov, to the Azeri President Geydar Aliyev, 
Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrosyan and Nagorno-Karabakh 
leader, Robert Kocharyan. 
  Depending on the reaction to this proposal by the sides 
concerned further steps are envisaged to cease combat operations 
in Nagorno-Karabakh. It is not ruled out that a meeting between 
the warring sides will take place in Moscow during this week. 
  Heavy fighting with alternative success have been going on 
around Nagorno-Karabakh since the second half of December, 1993. 
As a result of the bloodshed, several thousands people were 
reported dead and thousands others were injured, predominantly 
on the side launching an offensive. 
  New escalation of military operations is even more pointless 
because leaders of all warring sides admit that the conflict 
cannot be resolved by military means and come out in favour of 
its political settlement, a source from the Russian Foreign 
Ministry said. The repetition of the bloodshed seriously 
hampers peace-keeping efforts made both by Russia and 
international organisations, the same source said. 
  Russia, as a mediator, seeks to bridge the gap between the 
warring sides and convince them that they should immediately 
sign an agreement on the cessation of armed confrontation and 
prevent further destabilisation of the situation in the region. 
  Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev met with the head of 
Azeri foreign policy department, Gasan Gasanov, his Armenian 
counterpart, Vagan Papazyan, and a representative of the 
Nagorno- Karabakh leadership, Arkady Gukasyan, in Moscow in the 
second half of December, 1993. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-35897 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov021_p_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
