<H3> <TI>   Delegation To Leave for Moscow for Negotiations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS3101161994 Tallinn ETA NEWS BULLETIN in English 0807 GMT 
31 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS3101161994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA NEWS BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From 31 January RAHVA HAAL, PUHAPAEVALEHT, pp 1,6] </F>
  [Text] Monday, January 31 -- President Lennart Meri met 
Russian Ambassador Alexander Trofimov at the latter's request on 
Friday [28 January]. Ambassador Trofimov handed over an answer 
to the letter sent to Russian President Boris Yeltsin on January 
5. Yeltsin discussed the problems the negotiations have failed 
to solve so far and expressed his hope that a mutually 
acceptable solution would be found. 
  The Estonian delegation is to leave for Moscow today for 
another round of negotiations. Head of the delegation 
Ambassador Vaino Reinart said that all four groups of issues -- 
military, border, humanitarian and economic -- will be 
discussed. He hoped that the basic agreement on the troop 
withdrawal may be initialled this time. But he admitted the 
existence of disagreements on the compensation of the 
environmental damage and the armament confiscated in 1940, as 
well as the ownership of military establishments and the 
jurisdiction of the Russian military units. 
  Head of the Russian delegation Vasili Svirin announced that 
the Russian delegation will hand over the accurate troops 
withdrawal timetable at the February 1-2 round of negotiations. 
He added that the Estonian side is attempting to replace the 
basic agreement with a brief protocol on the troops withdrawal. 

</TEXT>

