<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israel Gives Captured Weapons to Estonia as Gift </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101153694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1422 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3101153694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] TAAS Israel Industries gave Kr [Krona] 20 Mn 
[Million] (8 Kr = 1 DM [German marks]) worth of weapons to 
Estonia as a gift. 
  Maje Preem, the Estonian Defense Ministry press secretary, 
told Interfax Monday that the weapons, in particular 
rapid-firing 23 mm guns, machine guns and other captured 
Soviet-made automatic weaponry, had arrived in Estonia last week. 
  In the press secretary's words, the gift was "a bit of a 
surprise" and no decision has been made as to who will receive 
it. 
  It arrived with a second lot of the Kr 40 Mn worth of 
weaponry that Estonia had earlier bought from the same company. 
(The first lot arrived in May 1993 - IF). 
  Estonia had signed a $49 Mn deal with the company on 
delivery 
of machine guns, assault rifles, rocket launchers and other 
weapons for the country's armed forces, border guards and police. 
  Some State Assembly deputies had criticized the deal, saying 
the government acted incompetently in making it and that the 
weapons were too expensive and did not meet NATO standards. 
(Estonia had officially announced before the deal was made that 
it would use those standards - IF). 
  The deal was discussed in parliament and ratified by it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

