<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Strives To Improve Public Safety </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS3101155994 Tallinn BNS in English 1401 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS3101155994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 31, BNS -- Pumping money into the 
police is not enough to guarantee security in Estonia, Interior 
Minister Heiki Arike told BNS at a press conference today. 
  In the minister's opinion, local governments should come up 
with money to install locks in the outer doors of big apartment 
houses, improve street lighting, and create systems to combat 
car stealing. 
  "This would certainly do a lot more good in the future than 
offering easy money to the police," Arike claimed. 
  The minister said his ministry is working out a national 
safety program. 
  "I don't think it is realistic to place hope in a pattern of 
a police state where strong police forces guarantee national 
security," Arike noted. "To achieve security, local governments, 
the police and all citizens must work closely together." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-35910 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov021_r_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-021 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guluzade: `Proper Political Basis' Needed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102155794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1446 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102155794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Azerbaijan's state advisor for foreign policy Vafa 
Guluzade believes that no peace talks are possible as long as 
one fifth of Azerbaijan's territory is occupied by Armenia. 
  He told INTERFAX that Armenia's armed forces must be removed 
from Azerbaijani territory, including Nagorno-Karabakh. 
According to foreign sources, 8,000 Armenian citizens fight on 
the side of the so-called Karabakh forces, he said. 
  "Azerbaijan's position is absolutely clear: We must liberate 
our territories," he said. He also pointed out that Baku would 
like to do so without losses on either side. He believes that 
this is quite possible given Armenia's goodwill and Russia's 
determination. 
  Assessing the possibility of locating Russian peace-keeping 
forces in the zone of the Karabakh conflict, he said that these 
forces might be located on the Azerbaijani-Armenian border and 
between the conflicting parties after Armenia removes its forces 
from the occupied territory. He noted, however, that 
peace-keeping forces may be sent to a country only on the 
latter's request. 
  Speaking about the possibility of holding talks in Moscow 
between the Azerbaijani and Armenian presidents with the Russian 
president's mediation, Guluzade said that a proper political 
basis must be created for such talks. "If Russia acts as a 
mediator, it must find a common denominator for settlement," he 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

