<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Update on Conflict With Armenia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101173694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1644 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3101173694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Azerbaijani Defense Ministry today reported that 
heavy fighting continued today in the area of the 
Armenian-Azerbaijani conflict. 
  According to sources in Baku, the Armenians lost 7 tanks and 
2 armored vehicles over the last two days of clashes in the 
Ter-Ter, Agdam and Fizuli districts. Casualties among Armenian 
troops are measured "in hundreds," the same sources said. 
  The ministry also said villages of the Kedabek, Agdam, 
Ter-Ter and Fizuli districts of Azerbaijan and the village of 
Sadarak of the Nakhichevan autonomous republic came under heavy 
artillery fire yesterday. The shelling left one person dead and 
another two wounded. 
  Sources in the Azerbaijani parliament report that Milli 
Mejlis Chairman Rasul Guliyev is visiting Azerbaijani positions 
looking into the situation along the front line and the back-up 
of Azerbaijani units. 
  Meanwhile, the press office of the Nagorno-Karabakh army 
told 
INTERFAX that Nagorno-Karabakh units were re-gaining control of 
the highland pass Omar situated in the north of the Kelbajar 
district of Azerbaijan. The press office said Azerbaijani units 
suffered huge casualties both in personnel and hardware. Over 
the last 24 hours, Azerbaijanis lost over 150 troops, 4 tanks 
T-72 and 2 armored vehicles, while only 6 Nagorno-Karabakh 
troops were killed and 18 wounded, according to the press office. 
  The press office also said two Azerbaijani combat jets 
Sukhoi-25 bombed villages and Nagorno-Karabakh positions in the 
north of the Martuni district today at noon. According to 
preliminary reports, the bombing left victims both among 
servicemen and civilians. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

