<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gasanov Stresses `Political Peaceful Solution' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101173194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1610 
GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3101173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [by ITAR-TASS correspondents Ssevindzh Adullayeva and Viktor </F>
Shulman] 
  [Text] Baku, 31 Jan -- Talks between Gasan Gasanov, 
Azerbaijan foreign minister, and Vladimir Kazimirov, special 
envoy of the Russian president and Russia's roving ambassador, 
lasted more than two hours behind "closed doors" today. The 
Russian diplomat, who arrived in the republican capital after 
visiting Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh, brought a draft agreement 
on cease-fire in the zone of the Armenian-Azerbaijani conflict. 
  In an interview with journalists after completing the talks 
Vladimir Kazimirov stressed that during his trip to the region 
the issues raised at the recent meetings in Moscow of the 
Russian foreign minister with the heads of the foreign political 
departments of Azerbaijan and Armenia were discussed. In his 
view, the positions of the sides involved in confrontation 
remain inflexible. He expressed the hope that, as an initial 
measure, an accord on a general cease-fire will be reached 
tonight. 
  According to Gasan Gasanov, Azerbaijan would benefit from 
signing an agreement on truce, either short or long-term. The 
republic, he stressed, adheres to a position of political 
peaceful settlement to the conflict. If Armenia undertakes to 
withdraw its troops from Azerbaijan, the latter, in turn, is 
ready to "immediately start talks and sign an agreement," the 
minister said. At the same time, touching upon Armenia's 
position, the head of the republican foreign political 
department noted that it has not changed significantly and 
remains inflexible. "Armenia is still trying to talk to 
Azerbaijan from a position of strength," Gasan Gasanov stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

