<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gasanov on Withdrawal Condition for Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101175294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1659 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3101175294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Sevindzh Abdullayeva and Viktor </F>
Shulman] 
  [Text] Baku January 31 TASS--Azerbaijan insists that 
Armenia should pledge withdrawal from occupied territories 
before a ceasefire can be agreed upon, while a Russian mediator 
said the ceasefire should come first and should be accompanied 
by the withdrawal. 
  "If Armenia pledges to withdraw its forces from the 
territory 
of Azerbaijan, Azerbaijan, in its turn, will be ready to 
immediately get down to talks and sign the (ceasefire) 
agreement", Foreign Minister of Azerbaijan Gasan Gasanov told 
reporters after meeting Russian envoy mediating the settlement 
in Nagorno-Karabakh Vladimir Kazimirov on Monday. 
  "It is profitable for Azerbaijan to sign the ceasefire 
agreement --whether short or long-term. The republic continues 
to adhere to the position of a political and peaceful settlement 
of the conflict", Gasanov said, but hinted, however, that the 
possibility is vague because, according to him, the Armenian 
position had not changed considerably and remains tough. 
  "Armenia continues to try and talk to Azerbaijan from 
positions of force", Gasanov stressed. 
  Kazimirov, who had visited Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh, 
agreed that the positions of both sides remain tough and urged 
them to be "more flexible". 
  "We would like to see more flexibility because the interests 
of the peoples whose blood is shed in the senseless conflict 
demand an early end to the bloodshed", Kazimirov said adding 
that Russia is ready to render any assistance in mediating a 
ceasefire. 
  He expressed hope that an agreement on a ceasefire beginning 
from this night will be reached and will become the first step 
towards a complete end to hostilities. 
  The complete end to combat activities should be "accompanied 
by the pullout of forces from seized territories, by the 
restoration of transport and energy-transmitting communications, 
by a return of refugees", Kazimirov said. 
  He complained that the warring sides "underestimate the 
necessity of an early end to hostilities" without which, 
according to him, it is impossible to efficiently settle the 
conflict. 
  Advantages in the military situation may go from one side to 
another while "people are paying for the calculations of 
political leaders", the Russian mediator said. 
  Both Gasanov and Kazimirov refused to say whether they had 
achieved any concrete results. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-35915 </DOCNO>
