<H3> <TI>   Aliyev Receives Kazimirov, Rejects Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC3101201494 Baku Azerbaycan Radio Televiziyasi Television 
Network in Azeri 1630 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC3101201494 </F>
<F P=104>  Baku Azerbaycan Radio Televiziyasi Television 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Azeri </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The Azerbaijani President Geydar Aliyev received 
today the Russian president's personal representative Vladimir 
Kazimirov. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified reporter] Is there any 
chance 
of yet another initiative by the Russian government succeeding? 
And, who stands to gain from Vladimir Kazimirov's visit to 
Azerbaijan? These were the questions which most concerned my 
colleagues who had come to shed light on the talks held today 
between President Geydar Aliyev and the Russian president's 
personal representative Vladimnir Kazimirov. 
  Vladimir Kazimirov again reiterated during this visit to 
Azerbaijan that Russia has not changed its previous proposals 
for the peaceful resolution of the conflict, and, in his 
opinion, it is far more appropriate and useful to renegotiate 
the peace conditions advanced during the previous consultations 
than to put forward a new idea each time. 
  Geydar Aliyev said that the Azerbaijani side has often 
supported the peace initiative and exerted every effort for the 
elimination of this meaningless war but every time the Armenian 
side attached no importance to these proposals. 
  Kazimirov noted that this time around the concrete aim of 
his 
visit to Baku was to submit proposals for the establishment of a 
cease-fire as of 1 February; and Russia calls on the sides to 
endorse this initiative by remaining in their present positions. 
  The Azerbaijani president replied to this proposal by 
advancing consistent and convincing evidence. [passage omitted] 
  Vladimir Kazimirov mentioned another point in an effort to 
have Aliyev change his mind. Kazimirov argued that a new 
chairman of CSCE Minsk Group has been appointed and it would be 
good if he took up his duties tomorrow morning with a report 
that a cease-fire has been achieved in Nagorno-Karabakh. 
  Geydar Aliyev's reply clarified this issue. [Aliyev 
statement in Russian omitted] 
  After the conversation, the republic's president announced 
his concrete proposals. [passage omitted] 
  Foreign Minister Gasan Gasanov, and State Adviser Vafa 
Gulizade were also present at the meeting. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

