<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Show Georgians Welcome Yeltsin Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101150594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1406 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3101150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Albert Kochetkov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 31 TASS -- The Georgian public is 
increasingly inclined to believe that Georgia's future is 
connected more with Russia rather than with the West, according 
to the results of a blitz public opinion poll conducted by the 
local newspaper "FREE GEORGIA." 
  A total of 51.2 per cent of respondents said that the 
forthcoming visit by the Russian president to Georgia will have 
a positive impact on the improvement of relations between the 
two countries, having age-old historical, economic and 
humanitarian ties. 
  Only 37.6 per cent of respondents were skeptical about the 
future of Russo-Georgian relations, while 4.7 per cent expect 
Russo-Georgian relations to worsen. 

</TEXT>

