<DOCNO> FBIS3-35926 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov021_s_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-021 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze: Leaders Oppose `Thaw' in Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101151094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1422 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3101151094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze stated that a 
thaw in Georgian-Russian relations was opposed by the Abkhazian 
leaders, because it undermined their separatist policies. 
  He told a closed conference in Tbilisi on Sunday that ways 
of 
settling the conflict in Abkhazia would figure prominently in 
the talks during Boris Yeltsin's visit beginning February 3. 
  This conference was attended by members of the organizing 
committee for Boris Yeltsin's visit, and details about it 
reached Interfax through well-informed sources in Tbilisi. 
  Shevardnadze announced that the Russian delegation would 
include Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev, Russian Defense 
Minister Pavel Grachev, and St. Petersburg Mayor Anatoliy 
Sobchak. 
  It was also announced that the guards of honor's uniforms 
did 
not meet the required standards and that new uniforms would be 
made for them within the next couple of days. In addition, it 
was indicated that the guards of honor are not properly trained 
either, while the military band's professional standards leave 
much to be desired, so the band of the Russian army group 
stationed in the Trans-Caucasus may be asked to play. 
  New motorcycles have been brought to Georgia for use in the 
honorary escort. Tbilisi's best hotel, Metekhi, will 
accommodate a press center which will maintain international 
telephone communications. 
  Some of Boris Yeltsin's security guards and part of the 
Russian delegation (consisting of a total of 46 members) have 
already arrived. 
  The Russian delegation is expected to have about 200 
members. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-35927 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov021_s_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-021 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abkhaz Servicemen Killed in Galskiy Rayon </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101210194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1854 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3101210194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] According to the Abkhazian Defense Ministry, during 
the past few days several assaults on Abkhazian military 
servicemen have been committed in the Galskiy region of the 
republic. 
  A car of the Abkhazian Armed Forces was shelled near the 
village of Otobaya on January 29. As a result, two soldiers 
were wounded and one killed. 
  Another 4 mutilated corpses of Abkhazian soldiers were found 
near the village of Sida. The Defense Ministry said that "all 
this was done by subversive groups of the Georgian Armed Forces." 
  A statement made public in Sukhumi on Monday says that in 
January 1994 units of Georgian gangsters had become more active 
in the Galskiy region. 
  Several crossings into the territory of Abkhazia by Georgian 
military groups were registered in January. 
  According to reports from Sukhumi, as a result of subversive 
and terrorist acts in the past 20 days alone 25 Abkhazian 
servicemen and 12 civilians were killed, and about 15 soldiers 
wounded. 
  The Defense Ministry stated that "it cannot tolerate such 
actions by Georgian group of gangsters and their supporters in 
the Galskiy region" and "will take decisive measures to 
eliminate them." 

</TEXT>

