<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Voices Idea of Federal State With Abkhazia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101201794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1924 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3101201794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Abert Kochetkov] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi January 31 TASS--A Georgian daily has for 
the first time publicly voiced the idea to turn Georgia into a 
federal state which can be assessed as a reconciliation hand 
extended to the rebel region of Abkhazia. 
  "Taking into consideration the experience of other countries 
and the current political situation it is necessary to recognise 
the necessity of a federal structure of Georgia", the 
Tbilisi-based "TEMI" (Assembly) newspaper said. 
  "Actually we are living today in a federative state without 
a 
federative constitution", it added. 
  The daily offered Germany as an example for the independent 
federative Georgian state. It added that autonomous republics 
had been artificially created in the former Soviet Union and 
resulted in bloodshed after the Soviet collapse. 
  Georgia has three autonomies--Abkhazia, South Ossetia and 
Adzharia. Only the latter succeeded to avoid a conflict. 
  Many Georgian politicians expressed similar ideas in 
interviews with TASS. However, every time they asked not to be 
named as the idea of federalism is assessed by the opposition as 
betrayal of national interests. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

