<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kavsadze Statement on 28 Jan Abkhaz Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102110394 Tbilisi Radio Tbilisi Network in Georgian 0500 
GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0102110394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi Radio Tbilisi Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Georgian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] This is a statement by Sandro Kavsadze, personal and 
plenipotentiary representative of the Georgian head of state, 
parliament chairman in the sphere of conflict settlement, and 
state committee chairman for human rights and interethnic 
relations. 
  On 28 January 1994, under the mediation of Russia and with 
the participation of representatives of the UN High Commissioner 
for Refugees, talks were held at the Russian Foreign Ministry 
between the Georgian and Abkhaz sides. 
  The talks lasted from 0900 till midnight but, unfortunately, 
ended without result. The four-party agreement on the voluntary 
repatriation of refugees and displaced persons was not 
implemented. 
  Many hours of exhausting work and searching for agreement 
and 
compromise produced a document. However, the Abkhaz side 
demanded from participants in the talks that persons wishing to 
return to permanent places of residence who had taken part in 
combat operations should not be covered by security guarantees. 
The Georgian side categorically refuses to discriminate between 
refugees on the grounds of their participation or 
non-participation in hostilities. Almost all the population, 
including Georgians, Abkhazians, and other nationalities living 
in Abkhazia, was involved in the conflict. 
  To punish people who took up arms to defend themselves and 
their relatives is a serious violation of human rights and an 
infringement of presumption of innocence. By blaming only the 
Georgian population, Gudauta makes another attempt to legitimize 
ethnic cleansing and disguise its desire to prevent a peaceful 
settlement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

