<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Observer Mission's Mandate Extended </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102112394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1052 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102112394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Sitnikov] </F>
  [Text] United Nations February 1 TASS -- The Security 
Council extended, until March 7, the mandate of a U.N. observer 
mission in the former Soviet republic of Georgia with a current 
authorised strength of 55, according to Resolution 896 which was 
unanimously adopted at the council meeting on Monday. 
  The U.N. Observer Mission in Georgia (UNOMIG) was set up in 
1993 to help end fighting between the Government of Georgia and 
Abkhazian separatist rebels. The council resolution expressed 
readiness to consider any recommendation from Secretary-General 
Butros Butros-Ghali in the next few weeks to increase the force 
up to a strength of 88. 
  It stressed the need for substantive progress in talks due 
to 
resume next month between the two sides on the political status 
of Abkhazia, fully respecting Georgia's sovereignty and 
territorial integrity. 
  Yuliy Vorontsov, permanent representative of the Russian 
Federation at the U.N., expressed support for the Georgian 
side's call to launch a full-scale peacekeeping operation 
throughout Abkhazia to ensure the return of refugees. He voiced 
regret that "at this stage the Security Council has been unable 
to comply with the request made by the Republic of Georgia." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

