<H3> <TI>   Parliament Decrees To Join International Pact </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0102120994 Tbilisi SAKARTVELOS RESPUBLIKA in Georgian 27 
Jan 94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU0102120994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi SAKARTVELOS RESPUBLIKA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Georgian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Three decrees of the Georgian Parliament on adherence to </F>
the international pacts on civil and political rights and on 
economic, social, and cultural rights issued in Tbilisi on 25 
January] 
  [Text] Decree of the Georgian Parliament on Adherence to 
the Optional Protocol of the International Pact on Civil and 
Political Rights 
  The Georgian Parliament decrees: 
  1. The Republic of Georgia is to adhere to the optional 
protocol of the International Pact on Civil and Political Rights. 
  2. To entrust the Republic of Georgia Ministry of Foreign 
Affairs with communicating this to the UN secretary general. 
  3. To entrust the Republic of Georgia Cabinet of Ministers 
with submitting proposals on bringing the republic's legislation 
into line with the norms of the optional protocol. 
  [Signed] Vakhtang Rcheulishvili, deputy speaker of the 
Georgian Parliament. 
  [Dated] Tbilisi, 25 January 1994. 
  Decree of the Georgian Parliament on Adherence to the 
International Pact on Civil and Political Rights 
  The Georgian Parliament decrees: 
  1. The Republic of Georgia is to adhere to the International 
Pact on Civil and Political Rights. 
  2. To entrust the Republic of Georgia Ministry of Foreign 
Affairs with communicating this to the UN secretary general. 
  3. To entrust the Republic of Georgia Cabinet of Ministers 
with submitting proposals on bringing the republic's legislation 
into line with the norms of this pact. 
  [Signed] Vakhtang Rcheulishvili, deputy speaker of the 
Georgian Parliament. 
  [Dated] Tbilisi, 25 January 1994. 
  Decree of the Georgian Parliament on Adherence to the 
International Pact on Economic, Social, and Cultural Rights 
  The Georgian Parliament decrees: 
  1. The Republic of Georgia is to adhere to the International 
Pact on Economic, Social, and Cultural Rights. 
  2. To entrust the Republic of Georgia Ministry of Foreign 
Affairs with communicating this to the UN secretary general. 
  3. To entrust the Republic of Georgia Cabinet of Ministers 
with submitting proposals on bringing the republic's legislation 
into line with the norms of this pact. 
  [Signed] Vakhtang Rcheulishvili, deputy speaker of the 
Georgian Parliament. 
  [Dated] Tbilisi, 25 January 1994. 

</TEXT>

