<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Russia National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Isakov on New Russian Constitution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2501182394 Moscow RIA in English 1516 GMT 25 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2501182394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow RIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, January 25, RIA -- The search for a version 
of the Constitution that would suit Russia best has been stopped 
only temporarily, says Chairman of the Duma Committee for 
Legislation and Judicial Reform Vladimir Isakov. Without 
putting the results of last December's constitutional vote in 
doubt, Mr. Isakov still maintained that the contradictions 
inherent in the new constitutions will require amendments in the 
near future. Mr. Isakov told RIA, in particular, that the 
Constitution does not remove many contradictions between the 
executive and legislative authorities in Russia. 
  At the same time, Mr. Isakov's interview implies that the 
former fervent proponents of the "Soviet" draft of the 
Constitution as opposed to Mr. Yeltsin's version have drawn 
lessons from last year's political developments and are not 
going to fan passions around the constitutional issue. Mr. 
Isakov said that the effort to elaborate cardinally new drafts 
of the Constitution will take place in the framework of public 
initiatives, but in no way in the Duma. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

