<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Holds News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Not Satisfied With Mandate on Georgia </H4>
<F P=102> LD0102163594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1607 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102163594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Aleksandr Krylovich] 
  [Text] Moscow February 1 TASS -- The Russian Foreign 
Ministry "is not fully satisfied" with the content of 
yesterday's resolution of the U.N. Security Council to prolong 
the U.N. observer mission mandate in Georgia, head of the 
Russian Foreign Ministry's information and press department 
Grigoriy Karasin told a briefing here today. 
  In the opinion of the Russian side, the mere prolongation of 
the mission mandate "can hardly be viewed as an adequate answer 
to the moderate but real progress achieved at Geneva 
negotiations in December 1993 and January 1994, repeated 
requests of the Georgian and Abkhazian side to send peace-makers 
to the conflict zone, and the real situation in the region." 
  Karasin expressed regret with the "lack of worthy response 
to 
Russian proposals of a genuine peace-making operation in 
Abkhazia". Further delay in such decision objectively confirms 
the current status quo -- isolation of Abkhazia and Georgia -- 
and freezes the soonest and safe return of refugees, which is a 
key humanitarian and political problem. 
  In the opinion of the Russian diplomat, this policy reduces 
chances for an agreement on political status of Abkhazia and 
increases the risk of a new bloodshed as result of spontaneous 
actions of refugees and displaced persons, whose number has 
reached 200,000 in the conflict zone. Karasin believes this 
reality should be foreseen. 
  "We are convinced that the introduction of peace-makers in 
the conflict zone is the only chance to achieve regional 
stabilization and create a real basis for final political 
settlement of the conflict, including the establishment of a 
political status of Abkhazia," he said. 
  In the opinion of the Russian Foreign Ministry, the mere 
beginning of a peace-making operation throughout Abkhazia by 
U.N. forces or other peace-makers authorized by the United 
Nations may create conditions for the implementation of 
agreements on lasting settlement by the warring sides. On its 
part, Russia is ready to make a positive answer to the sides' 
requests for its participation in the operation. 
  Karasin expressed the hope the U.N. secretariat will timely 
consider military-technical, financial and other aspects of a 
peace-making operation in Abkhazia in accordance with the U.N. 
Security Council's resolution of January 31, 1994, in order to 
enable members of the Security Council to discuss the operation 
in detail and decide on its beginning. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-35965 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov022_a_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-022 </AU>
