<DATE1>  2 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Holds News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Views Proposal on Karabakh Conflict </H4>
<F P=102> LD0102180494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1752 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102180494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Aleksandr Krylovich] 
  [Text] Moscow February 1 TASS -- A new Russian proposal on 
global cease-fire from February 1 through minimum two or three 
weeks has been presented by special representative of the 
Russian president Vladimir Kazimirov to Azeri President Geydar 
Aliyev, Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrosyan and Karabakh 
Leader Robert Kocharyan, head of the Russian Foreign Ministry's 
Information and Press Department Grigoriy Karasin told a 
briefing here today. 
  "Depending on the sides' reaction to the proposal, Russia 
plans further steps aiming at termination of combat operations 
in Nagorno- Karabakh," said the diplomat. 
  Bloody fighting around Nagorno-Karabakh has been on since 
the 
second half of December 1993. It has claimed the lives of 
several thousands of people and wounded another several 
thousands, mainly the attackers. 
  "The new escalation of combat operations is even more 
senseless as heads of all the warring sides admit the conflict 
has no military solution and make statements favoring political 
settlement. The bloodshed recurrence hampers peace-making 
efforts of Russia and international organizations," stressed the 
Foreign Ministry spokesman. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

