<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Popov Denies He Objects to Alliance With United States </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102204294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1731 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102204294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Gavriil Popov, chairman of the Russian Democratic 
Reform Movement (RDRM), denied a report published in the 
February 1 edition of the NOVAYA YEZHEDNEVNAYA GAZETA (NEW 
DAILY) to the effect that he told his group's convention he 
wanted the alliance-style relations with the United States 
discontinued. 
  "I did not mention any issue related to alliance relations 
with the U.S.A. in my report," Popov told INTERFAX Tuesday. In 
his words, the RDRM wants "Russia to seek long-term allies and 
the U.S.A. can be one of them." 
  He also denied having said that the RDRM platform called for 
"large scale government control and financing." 
  Popov thinks that "reliance on the West and the Western 
development option did not work in the sense that the West was 
unable to offer resources for reforms in Russia and the recipes 
the West offered Russia made the situation here worse." 
  He emphasized that "the International Monetary Fund's 
recipes 
were not what the developed countries had used themselves but 
what they had offered to underdeveloped countries." 
  "What they had to offer to Russia was a Latin American 
option," Popov said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

