<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Zhirinovskiy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102174994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1730 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102174994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Georgy Shmelyov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 1 TASS -- Russian Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev mocked the idea that inflammatory statements of 
nationalist leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky can influence the 
position of any of the three warring sides in Bosnia and 
proposed to hold a competition for the best tablet for 
Zhirinovsky. 
  The tablets should be for "hysteria, suspicion and other 
types of devilish possession". "There is a feeling that 
Zhirinovsky has succeeded in creating the situation of hysteria 
and suspicion", Kozyrev told reporters after meeting 
international mediators Lord Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg on 
Tuesday. 
  He was evidently referring to statements of Zhirinovsky who 
said that air strikes on Bosnian Serbs will be viewed as an 
attack on Russia and promised to use an alleged secret sonic 
weapon in retaliation. 
  But Kozyrev expressed hope that there would be no air 
strikes 
on Bosnia although the possibility is not ruled out in the 
framework of the UN Security Council resolutions and only in 
"extreme cases". 
  He added that "punishment strikes" are "absolutely 
inadmissible". 
  However, the foreign minister admitted that "hypothetically 
the possibility of air strikes exists" in case UN peace-keepers 
are attacked by any of the conflicting sides while fulfilling 
their humanitarian mission. 
  Kozyrev said that the UN secretary general had named 
Srebrenica and Tuzla as the regions where a threat to UN forces 
exist. "Luckily, talks with the Serbian side resulted in an 
agreement on help in replacing the Canadian battalion with a 
Dutch one. Diplomatic work to unblock the situation in Tuzla is 
going on which is possible with a direct Russian participation", 
Kozyrev said adding that attacks on UN convoys are staged not 
only by Serbs, but by Muslims and Croats as well. 
  Lord Owen thanked Russia for "a very constructive role" on 
all stages of the work to reach a political settlement. 
  None of the three warring parties can secure a military 
victory and a solution can be found only at the negotiating 
table, he told TASS. 
  He expressed hope that the conflicting sides will resume 
negotiations in the coming weeks to "find a compromise on those 
inconsiderable contradictions which still exist". 
  Owen urged to continue humanitarian aid supplies to the 
civilian population in conditions of a harsh winter. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

