<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnia Mediators' Arrival, Zhirinovskiy Remarks Linked </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0102193994 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 2 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM0102193994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Sergey Sidorov: "Green Light to Use Air Power in </F>
Bosnia"] 
  [Excerpts] UN Secretary General Butrus-Ghali's decision 
to give the green light to the use of air power in Bosnia to 
support the relief of the Canadian battalion in Srebrenica and 
the opening of the airport in Tuzla continues to prompt a 
variety of comment from officials, experts, and the press. 
[passage omitted] 
  On Tuesday international mediators T. Stoltenberg and David 
Owen (EU) arrive in Moscow for consultatuions. The Russian 
leadership's position, which will be set out for them at the 
Foreign Ministry, will probably differ from the pronouncements 
by LDPR [Liberal Democratic Party of Russia] leader Vladimir 
Zhirinovskiy, who said in Belgrade that the bombing of Serbs in 
Bosnia will mean a declaration of war on Russia. Nonetheless, 
the mediators will again be advised to think twice before 
reaching decisions on Bosnia. Their talks with the Russian 
Federation foreign minister will probably center on the new 
Russian initiatives and the future of the International 
Conference on the Former Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

