<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Big Changes in Ties With Ukraine, Belarus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102121794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1042 
GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0102121794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 1 Feb -- "Russia's relations with Ukraine 
and Belarus will not change significantly with the election of 
Yuriy Meshkov as president of Crimea or the removal of Stanislav 
Shushkevich from the post of speaker of the Belarus parliament," 
Sergey Krasavchenko, first deputy head of the Russian 
presidential administration, told the ITAR-TASS correspondent. 
  According to him, "relations between the three CIS states 
will be implemented within the framework of the strategy and 
political course determined during the meetings of leaders of 
the Commonwealth and in bilateral agreements." 
  If Belarus adopts a position toward Russia that differs from 
that under Stanislav Shuskevich, "the appropriate reaction from 
Russia will follow, too. And the same applies to Ukraine," 
Sergey Krasavchenko noted. 
  The advent to power of Yuriy Meshkov, president of Crimea, 
who is a radical supporter of the peninsula becoming a sovereign 
entity "may complicate relations between Russia and Ukraine, if 
certain forces strive to draw Russia into the nascent conflict." 
However, he stressed, "there are normal, civilized, political 
methods" that may help avert confrontation. Recalling the 
statement by Yuriy Meshkov that he does not intend to seek 
Crimea's immediate departure from Ukraine and its annexation to 
Russia, Sergey Krasavchenko noted that "no major grounds for 
tension should arise." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-35981 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov022_a_94020" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-022 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia's Choice Opposes Financial Union With Belarus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102130994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1114 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102130994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The State Duma's Russia's Choice faction, led by 
former first deputy prime minister Yegor Gaydar, opposes plans 
for the unification of the Russian and Belarusian monetary 
systems, claiming they are hasty and badly prepared. 
  "In their current form, the inter-bank and 
inter-governmental 
agreements will undoubtedly inflict colossal economic damage on 
Russia, spur inflation, and sharply bring down the Russian 
citizens' living standards," says the faction's statement 
circulated on Monday. 
  The document says, however, that Russia's Choice favors 
Russia's economic integration with Belarus and other former 
Soviet republics on clear-cut terms. The terms on which the two 
states' monetary systems might be united are as follows: 
  1. The unification of the budget, taxing, crediting, 
financial, customs, foreign-trade and monetary legislation; 
  2. The levelling of the two states' economic indices, above 
all the budget deficit, and the rates of credit emission and 
inflation; 
  3. The Belarusian national currency shall be exchanged for 
the ruble at a rate fixed on the free currency market; 
  4. Credits and cash shall come strictly from one emission 
center. 
  Only on these terms will integration be equitable and 
mutually advantageous for the states concerned, says Russia's 
Choice. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

