<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abkhazia Against Georgian-Russian Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102121194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1034 
GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0102121194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Irina Shchegoleva] </F>
  [Text] Sochi, 1 Feb -- "We are against the signing of a 
treaty on friendship and cooperation between Russia and Georgia, 
planned for 3 February," said Sokrat Dzhindzholiya, chairman of 
the Abkhaz Council of Ministers, on behalf of the Abkhaz 
government to an ITAR-TASS correspondent this morning. He 
believes this treaty "will enable Georgia to have access to 
Russian weapons." Sokrat Dzhindzholiya believes the treaty on 
friendship and cooperation between Russia and Georgia can only 
be signed after a comprehensive settlement of the 
Georgian-Abkhaz conflict, which is impossible without defining 
Abkhazia's political status. 
  "During the recent talks in Geneva, only a first step was 
made toward the settlement of the conflict," underlined Sokrat 
Dzhindzholiya. "The threat of renewed fighting still exists, 
and the question of peacekeeping forces for the conflict zone 
has been raised. In such conditions, the signing of a treaty 
with Georgia is fraught with very serious consequences." 
  The chairman of the Abkhaz Council of Ministers said leaders 
of North Caucasian republics within Russia share his point of 
view. 

</TEXT>

