<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin Comments on Eve on Yeltsin Georgia Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102143194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1410 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102143194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 1 TASS -- "We are not prepared to 
admit Georgia into the ruble zone," chairman of the Russian 
Government Viktor Chernomyrdin told journalists on Tuesday on 
the eve of Russian president's visit to Georgia scheduled on 
February 3. 
  Chernomyrdin said that during previous meetings with 
Georgian 
leaders the question of Georgia's entering the ruble zone was 
not discussed. 
  The Russian prime minister believes that this problem might 
be considered in the context of the realisation of the economic 
union between CIS countries. He pointed out that countries 
joining the ruble zone will have to sacrifice part of their 
sovereignty and carry out tough coordination of economic reforms 
between themselves. 
  In connection with the January statement made by Russian and 
Belarusian leadership on Belarus' entering the ruble zone 
Chernomyrdin pointed out that "it is naive to suppose that this 
will happen at the expense of Russian tax-payers." 
Chernmomyrdin pointed out that Belarus is not going to live at 
Russia's expense. "Admitting Belarus into the ruble zone will 
not be detrimental to Russia's interests. We shall not let it 
happen," Chernomyrdin declared. [as received] 
  Chernomyrdin believes that one cannot speak today about an 
anti- reformist policy of the Belarusian leadership. "I see 
that the Belarusian Government is targeted at reforms," he added. 

</TEXT>

