<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tape of Japanese Fishing Boat Incident at Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102075894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0740 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102075894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vyacheslav Bantin] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo February 1 TASS -- Russian border guards 
video-filmed the recent incident during which 130-140 Japanese 
fishing boats crossed Russia's state border in the area of south 
Kurils and the actions of the Russian border patrol ships, 
Colonel-General Andrey Nikolayev, commander-in-chief of Russia's 
frontier forces, told ITAR-TASS. He arrived here to attend a 
three-sided forum, opening on Tuesday, of representatives from 
Russia, the United States and Japan on security in the northern 
Pacific. 
  Nikolayev said he brought the video film to Tokyo and is 
prepared to show it to Japanese experts if they would wish so. 
  On Monday a spokesman for Japan's Maritime Safety Agency 
(MSA) told ITAR-TASS that the agency "did not put on record" 
massive intrusions by Japanese fishing boats into Russian 
territorial waters on January 21-22, which had been the subject 
of a Russian Foreign Ministry representation made to Tokyo. 
  In view of this, the MSA, which partially performs the 
functions of frontier units, dropped the inquiry into whether 
Japanese boats crossed the state border of the Russian 
Federation. 
  It has become known from informed sources that last year 
Russian border guards recorded about 7,000 transgressions of the 
border by Japanese fishing boats. Practically no transgressors 
were apprehended to avoid a conflict with the neighbouring state. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

