<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Medvedev Fears Anti-Reform `Belt' Around Moscow </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102144494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1416 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 1 TASS -- "The eternal Russian 
question, `who will defeat whom', might be at the centre of the 
upcoming local elections", according to the worried assessment 
of Nikolay Medvedev, head of the Russian presidential 
administration's department for work with the territories. 
  Medvedev told ITAR-TASS on Tuesday there is a danger that 
the 
federal government will support reforms, "while opposition 
forces might come to power at the regional and republican 
level". And no matter how constructive the efforts of reformers 
in the centre are, they don't stand a chance without the support 
of Russia's regions, he declared. 
  One of the problems revealed by the unfolding local 
campaigns 
is, Medvedev explained, that "despite reformers' calls for 
unification, in actuality we don't have any party structures in 
the regions". Those parties who do have local power structures 
are the Communist Party and others of the same leaning. They 
are now restoring their organisations and will, of course, do 
everything they can to defeat the reformers in the upcoming 
local elections, Medvedev said. The economic and financial 
difficulties in the regions play into the hands of the 
opposition forces. 
  Medvedev voiced his opinion that reformers can improve their 
alarming electoral prospects by "honestly explaining their 
mistakes made in socio-economic and financial policy, which did 
not take reality into account". After recognizing its mistakes, 
the Russian Government "should, as soon as possible, determine 
how it is going to correct its reform policy". "There is a hope 
that the president's address, to be delivered to parliament on 
February 18, will be the starting point of a socially-orientated 
policy", Medvedev pointed out. 
  In his analysis of elections already held in Moscow, the 
Moscow and Tula regions, and tens of other districts, Medvedev 
said he thinks the current office-holders are better than their 
predecessors. Therefore, he supposed, if the democratic forces 
can unite their efforts, they can be successful in other regions 
as well. 
  However, the presidential adviser admitted, he has little 
reason for optimism, since "we cannot rule out the possibility 
of the formation of a sort of 'red belt' around Moscow", which 
would be made up of regions with anti-reform and anti-president 
mind-sets: Tambov, Oryol, Voronezh, Lipetsk, Ryazan, Mordoviya, 
and Penza". 
  Medvedev was able to find one observation which he could 
call 
"comforting". During his trips around the country, he met with 
various political leaders. From his meetings, Medvedev 
concluded that many of them, including opposition politicians, 
are taking a second look at their potential allies, especially 
Zhirinovskiy's party with its inflammatory statements. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-36022 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov022_b_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-022 </AU>
