<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Dniester Republic' To Block Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102153094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1420 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102153094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Demidetskiy] </F>
  [Text] Chisinau February 1 TASS -- The Dniester authorities 
will thwart the elections to the Moldovan parliament on its 
territory, Valeri Litskay, state secretary of the unrecognised 
Dniester republic, told ITAR-TASS on Tuesday. 
  If the Moldovan leadership sends mobile polling stations and 
foreign observers to the Dniester region, they will be barred by 
armed patrols which are stationed on bridges across the Dniester 
in compliance with the state of emergency proclaimed in the 
Dniester region. 
  Incidentally, the Dniester parliament adopted a decision on 
Tuesday to hold elections to local bodies of self-rule next 
April. 
  Within the next two months, a special commission is to 
submit 
a new concept of local self-rule to the Dniester parliament in 
connection with the new political and economic situation in the 
region. Several local lawmakers suggested that a referendum on 
the Dniester republic's future should be held along with the 
elections. 
  Moldovan Deputy Parliament Speaker Viktor Pushkash described 
these actions of Tiraspol authorities as "anticonstitutional and 
contravening international laws". According to the deputy 
speaker, many voters on the Dniester west bank wish to 
participate in the elections, which is corroborated by letters 
coming to Chisinau and telephone calls. 
  "However, armed patrols stationed by the Tiraspol leaders on 
all roads turned the territory into a reservation of a kind," 
Pushkash stressed. "I'm sure," he continued, "that the Dniester 
leaders will raise difficulties for those who will want to vote 
and try to prevent people from going to the right bank. 
  "Despite an opposition from the Tiraspol leaders, we meet 
and 
will meet our voters in left-bank districts and will try to 
provide them will a chance to vote on the election day." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

