<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Snegur: Links With Former USSR States `Vital' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101212094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1854 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3101212094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moldovan President Mircea Snegur said it was in 
Moldova's vital interests to maintain its links with other 
former Soviet republics. 
  This would provide a basis for surmounting the present 
economic crisis in Moldova, Snegur told U.S. Congress expert 
Sergio Verona in Chisinau on Monday. 
  But Moldova would join no political or military CIS 
treaties, 
for it wanted to remain "genuinely neutral," he said. 
  Going over to the problem of Transdniestria, Snegur said the 
leaders of the mainly Russian-speaking enclave refused to start 
a dialogue with the Moldovan government, since the latter 
rejected their idea of confederative structure for Moldova. 
  Commenting on Moldova's relations with Romania, Snegur said 
those advocating unification between Moldova and Romania 
"thereby put up obstacles to the economic and cultural mutual 
integration of the two states." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

