<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rybkin, Yeltsin Discuss Cooperation With State Duma </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102134694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1259 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102134694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 1 TASS -- Ivan Rybkin, speaker of 
the State Duma (lower chamber of the Russian parliament), 
presented President Boris Yeltsin with a bouquet of red roses, 
since Yeltsin's name-day is on Tuesday [1 February]. 
  ITAR-TASS learnt from Valeriy Gerasimov, head of the State 
Duma's office, that "the meeting between the two lasted 45 
minutes instead of the planned ten". The sides discussed 
cooperation between the president and the lower house. 
  Asked by ITAR-TASS about the meaning of the notion 
"succession of the State Duma" which will be debated at the 
Duma's session this Friday, Gerasimov replied that "we mean 
succession from pre-revolutionary time, since the present State 
Duma is not the first in Russian history". 
  According to Gerasimov, legislators intend to study valuable 
experience accumulated by Russian dumas before and after 1917, 
mindful also of positive achievements of the former Russian 
parliament. 
  Gerasimov refuted rumours about a possible intention by the 
State Duma to put forth property claims, saying that the lower 
chamber intends to dissociate itself from petty property issues. 
  According to Gerasimov, the State Duma will deal only with 
projects which cannot be financed from local budgets, including 
the State Duma library in St. Petersburg as well as the 
Tavricheskiy Palace in the same city where inter-parliamentary 
assemblies of the Commonwealth of Independent States are held. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-36036 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov022_c_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-022 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Elects Heads of Committees </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102151994 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102151994 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian at 
1320 GMT on 1 February broadcasts a report by Aleksandr 
Ruvinskiy in the studio. He says that many Federation Council 
deputies came to Chekhov St. to pay their last respects to actor 
Yevgeniy Leonov. As there was no morning session the deputies 
had plenty of spare time. They spent the time holding the first 
organizational sessions of committees and commissions of the 
Federation Council. 
  Whereas, he says, in the Duma, the Duma Council met and 
agreed on who would head the committees, these people were 
ratified by overall vote and then each deputy could register in 
one committee or another. 
  On the other hand, here in the Federation Council it was 
different. First, the composition of the actual committees was 
formed, and then within these committees the deputies themselves 
elected their own chairmen. This is because a factional party 
principle does not operate in the Federation Council. 
  There were some surprises, Ruvinskiy continues. Vyacheslav 
Zvolinskiy became chairman of the Agrarian Committee. He is 
director of the scientific production association Nizhnyaya 
Volga in Astrakhan. On this committee are such deputies as 
Vasiliy Starodubtsev, [Vyacheslav] Lyubimov from Ryazan, an 
active member of the Communist Party, and others. Today, the 
first session of the committee was held. 
  The first session of the Committee for Budget and Finance 
was 
also held. On this committee, deputies elected Nikolay Gonchar 
as their chairman, former chairman of Mossovet. Also on this 
committee are such deputies as Yuriy Boldyrev, well-known from 
the Congress of USSR People's Deputies and the Supreme Soviet. 
  Ruvinskiy then speaks to Boldyrev. He says that Boldyrev 
told him that he considers one of his main tasks as being to do 
everything necessary to fight corruption. He thinks a chamber 
of accounts should be set up and there should be a law on 
responsibility of government members for nonimplementation of 
legislation and for inappropriate expenditure. 
  Ruvinskiy and the announcer discuss the question of 
extending 
the emergency in North Ossetia and Ingushetia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

