<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Members Differ on Crimea </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK0102112094 Moscow MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS in Russian 1 Feb 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK0102112094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Yuriy Zaynashev report under the general headline: </F>
"Crimea: Kiev Is Preparing an Attack, Russia Prefers To 
Abstain"] 
  [Text] Yesterday, the Federation Council in Moscow 
discussed the Crimean issue only in the lobby. In an interview 
for MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS, Eduard Rossel, the failed governor 
of the Urals Republic, waved his hand enthusiastically: "Crimea 
is a Russian land, and I favor its being reclaimed by Russia as 
soon as possible." When asked by MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS how 
much time the construction of a dam or a bridge across the Kerch 
strait will take, Mr. Rossel, of German origin, revealed that he 
knew firms that could cope with such an order fairly quickly. 
The bridge that would connect the Russian Federation with 
Crimea could be built vertically and lowered later when the 
situation allows. The cautious Nikolay Gonchar, guarding his 
reputation as a centrist, said that Crimean President Yuriy 
Meshkov is a good and calm person, but that Moscow and Kiev 
should touch upon the Crimean issue very carefully so as not to 
carry matters to the brink of war. Mr. Gonchar called on both 
the president and the Federation Council to agree on a common 
stand on the Crimean issue so as not to transplant local 
passions to Moscow. Formerly, the stances of the president and 
the Russian Supreme Soviet regarding Crimea were diametrically 
opposed, a fact that was skillfully exploited by Crimean 
extremists. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

