<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier: No Future for Centralized Management </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102183594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1641 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102183594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature:] </F>
  [Text] [Tajikistan's] Prime Minister Abduljalil Samadov 
says attempts to try to maintain the command system of economic 
management are hopeless. 
  In a published appeal to the people, Samadov said that all 
official talks were now focused on mutual sales and payments but 
not on former obligatory sale to the state. He says the 
existing realities place the need for program correctives and 
the arrangement of normal market relations in domestic and 
foreign trade. 
  Samadov called on Tajik citizens to come up with coherent 
proposals on how to improve the functioning of economic 
mechanisms and effectively utilize the country's natural and 
human resources. He hopes that the system of accounting for as 
diversity of views will work on a permanent basis rather than 
being a short-lived time campaign. [sentence as received] 
  Many say the Prime Minister's call is intended to arrange 
close cooperation between the government and private sector in 
the effort to embrace economic reforms. 

</TEXT>

