<H3> <TI>   Economics Minister on `Tightening the Belt' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0102220194 Yerevan SNARK in English 1211 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0102220194 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan SNARK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yerevan, February 1 (SNARK)--Armenia falls into the 
medium degree of classification with the status of a less 
developed country. There is nothing wrong with this 
international status we got not so long ago, for over the last 
three years the gross national product has abruptly fallen. 
This information was told to SNARK today by the Armenian 
Minister for Economics Armen Yegiazaryan. He states that the 
real gross national product in 1990 was on the level of 4 700 
[figure as received] dollars per head. Last year it became 
700-800 dollars per head. 
  In Yegiazaryan's opinion, it would be incorrect to increase 
the incomes artificially, and at this stage there is no 
alternative to the policy of "tightening the belt". The 
minister thinks the three indexations of wages since January 1 
speak in favor of this assertion, as in conformity with the 
expectations there was no essential rise of the prices. "We have 
a situation in Armenia when the insolvency of the mainstream led 
to the drastic consumers' market contraction and, therefore, 
supply decrease", concluded the minister for economics. 

</TEXT>

