<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian-Speaking Assembly Issues Statement Against Racism </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0102153894 Tallinn BNS in English 1155 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0102153894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Feb 01, BNS--The Representative Assembly of 
Estonia's Russian-speaking Population proposes to arrange this 
year a forum of the country's democratic forces to mark the 50th 
anniversary of Estonia's liberation from fascist occupation. 
  The assembly suggests that the forum work out a program for 
joint action under the motto, "For healing the society, against 
nationalism, interethnic animosity and moral degradation." 
  "The seemingly eradicated fascism is again raising its head, 
sometimes under the guise of false liberalism, sometimes hiding 
behind patriotic slogans, and sometimes even quite openly," the 
assembly said in a statement adopted at its Jan. 29 session. 
"Not to notice it is dangerous; not to take action, criminal." 
  The assembly calls on all Estonian social and political 
forces to aim their efforts at stabilizing the society, 
improving interethnic relations and "guaranteeing human rights 
in reality." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

