<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Holds News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   `Satisfied' With FRY Report </H4>
<F P=102> LD0102151694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1455 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102151694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Aleksandr Krylovich] 
  [Text] Moscow February 1 TASS -- Russia is satisfied with a 
report saying the Yugoslav authorities have offered information 
on their Armed Forces as of January 1, 1994, to CSCE for the 
first time since disintegration of former Yugoslavia, head of 
the Russian Foreign Ministry's Information and Press Department 
Grigoriy Karasin told a briefing here today. 
  A document circulated by Yugoslav representatives in Vienna 
says the Yugoslav Army does not plan to deploy additional types 
of heavy armaments or combat systems on Yugoslav territory in 
1994, said the Russian Foreign Ministry's spokesman. 
  "Information on location of forces and their armaments 
against the background of the on-going combat operations in 
Bosnia and Herzegovina testifies to the Yugoslav interest in 
military security and stability in the region," said Karasin. 

</TEXT>

