<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Holds News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Calls For Negotiated Peace in Afghanistan </H4>
<F P=102> LD0102155394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1456 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102155394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia calls for a negotiated settlement to the 
conflict in Afghanistan on the basis of compromise by the 
Afghans themselves, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said in Moscow 
on Tuesday [1 February]. 
  Reports from Afghanistan, he said, speak of continuing 
clashes between different factions. Obviously, not only does 
the emerging situation run counter to the interests of the 
Afghan people but poses a real threat to regional security as 
well, the spokesman said. 
  The official says Moscow is taking necessary steps within 
the 
framework of the UN and during bilateral contacts with states 
concerned as part of efforts to step up international help 
towards a political settlement in Afghanistan. 
  One of the elements of Russia's Afghanistan policy is to try 
to get Central Asian states involved in multilateral efforts for 
normalization in that country, the spokesman said. In his 
words, appropriate consultations are now under way with 
Uzbekistan. 
  A series of reports trying to gauge Uzbekistan's actions in 
connection with the Afghan crisis do not reflect Moscow's 
official position, the spokesman said. 

</TEXT>

