<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Will Not Repeat `Mistakes' on Crimea </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102172894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1650 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102172894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 1 TASS -- Russia's new parliament 
will not repeat the mistakes of the previous legislature and 
avoid extremist declarations on the situation in the Crimea, 
Vice Chairman of the Russian Parliamentary Committee on 
Commonwealth Affairs Vyacheslav Igrunov told ITAR-TASS Tuesday 
[1 February], commenting on the results of the presidential 
elections in the peninsula. 
  He evidently referred to the extremist statement of former 
legislature to declare the major Black Sea Fleet base in the 
Crimea, the port of Sevastopol, as Russian territory. 
  However, Russia should increase its political activity in 
the 
peninsula and be a guarantor of the stability in this autonomous 
republic of Ukraine, Igrunov stressed. 
  He welcomed the idea of establishing a Russian consulate or 
a 
permanent mission of the Russian parliament in Simferopol, the 
Crimean administrative centre. The parliamentarian also spoke 
in favour of the exchange of lawmakers' delegations between 
Russia and the Crimea. 
  Kiev should only praise such cooperation, as Moscow is not 
interested in the Crimean separatism, he stressed. Igrunov 
believes Ukraine should prefer the civilized cooperation with 
Russia to "an endless tug-of-war". 
  The parliamentarian said that he had just returned from the 
Crimea and Kiev after the on-spot examination of the situation. 
According to him, the first popularly elected president of the 
autonomy, Yuriy Meshkov should avoid hasty steps and rely on the 
renowned local politicians and parliament leaders. 

</TEXT>

