<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Reassures North Caucasus Leaders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0202090194 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 2 Feb 94 First 
Edition p 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM0202090194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Boris Vinogradov report: "Andrey Kozyrev: Russia Is Not </F>
Creating a New Military Alliance in the Caucasus"] 
  [Text] The Russian President's trip to Georgia will be B. 
Yeltsin's first official visit to a Commonwealth state, leaving 
aside his fleeting visit to Ashgabat and his talks with 
Saparmurad Niyazov. 
  The political nuances of the visit were examined at Andrey 
Kozyrev's conference with North Caucasus leaders. As the 
minister remarked, this is a major step aimed at implementing a 
strategic line in the Caucasus, which Russia has traditionally 
regarded as a zone of its geopolitical interests. Russia would 
not like to have on its border a state torn apart by internal 
conflicts and drowning in economic chaos and crime. 
  The preconditions for establishing cooperation have been 
created. Georgia has become a member of the CIS and the 
Collective Security Council. But it remains the only neighbor 
with which Moscow does not have a framework treaty on the bases 
of relations or agreements on border questions. The Russian 
delegation is taking a set of these documents with it to 
Tbilisi, where it intends to sign them. There is nothing in 
them that conflicts with the interests of the North Caucasus 
republics. They have no grounds for suspecting that any kind of 
"military-political alliance" is being prepared between Russia 
and Georgia against Abkhazia, the minister stressed. 
  One of the main tasks of the visit is to promote the 
settlement of conflicts in Abkhazia and South Ossetia. 
  Andrey Kozyrev pointed out that in principle Russia has 
decided to conduct peace-keeping operations in Abkhazia and 
intends to seek the participation of UN and CSCE international 
observers in it. The minister recognized at this point that 
Russia bears the main burden of the peacemaking work and the 
protection of people's lives, Georgia's sovereignty, and the 
rights of the ethnic minorities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

