<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lawmakers Demand Criminal Case Against Zvyahilskyy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302094794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0927 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302094794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Nekrasova] </F>
  [Text] Lvov February 3 TASS--The Ukrainian 
Procurator-General's Office accepted for examination a message 
by legislator Khmara and some of his colleagues where they 
demand that a criminal case be instituted against acting Premier 
Yukhym Zvyahilskyy who permitted 17 leading engineering 
factories to ship their products to countries of the 
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) without preliminary 
payment. 
  In legislators' opinion, this is "an illegal order 
inflicting 
material damage on Ukraine". 
  The difficult economic situation in the CIS countries has 
brought about a situation when some enterprises and 
organisations went bankrupt and did not pay for delivered goods 
or paid with great delays. 
  Former Ukrainian Premier Leonid Kuchma forbid to ship goods 
to former Soviet republics without preliminary payment or 
without guarantees by a foreign bank which could vouch for 
payments in time. 
  But, six months later, Zvyahilskyy signed a decision 
permitting the Kiev Elektronmash, Kharkov bicycle factories and 
other leading engineering enterprises to deliver goods to the 
CIS countries without the confirmation of preliminary payments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

