<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister `Satisfied' With CSCE Activity </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0202143294 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 1855 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0202143294 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Chisinau, BASAPRESS, 1/2/1994 -- The new head of 
CSCE [Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe] Mission 
to Moldova Richard Christopher Samuel (Great Britain), had today 
his first meeting with Ion Botnaru, Minister ad interim of 
Foreign Affairs (temporarily dismissed during the elections). 
Botnaru stated that so far Moldovan officials are satisfied 
with the results of CSCE Mission's activity. CSCE Mission 
recommendations on setting the Dniester conflict were examined 
at the highest level and are accepted as a basis for continuing 
the negotiations. The minister said the recent events in 
Dniester denote an agony of the unconstitutional structures and 
that Tiraspol regime loses its social basis. "We almost reached 
an agreement on granting a special juridical status to East 
districts, in the context of territorial and administrative 
reform and decentralization of power. Of course, it does not 
mean federalization or division of territories," pointed out 
Botnaru. He added the most destabilizing external factor is the 
presence of Russian 14th Army in Moldova. Samuel stated to BASA 
that he is just getting acquainted with Mission's activity. He 
wishes to travel trough Moldova and waits for the Thursday [3 
February] meeting with President Snegur in order to contact the 
sides involved in the controversies. Samuel also asserted that 
"Mission's main purpose is to accomplish the CSCE Mandate 
continuing to activate in directions established and supported 
by his predecessors." It is not the moment to make concrete 
proposals; we will resume our work where it was finished and we 
will find new possibilities for positive involvement of CSCE," 
said Samuel. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

