<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Snegur Notes Deteriorating Situation in Dniester </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202192394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1721 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202192394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature No. 22 for 2 </F>
February 1994; by Andrey Pershin, Andrey Petrovskiy, and 
Vladimir Shishlin; edited by Boris Grishchenko] 
  [Text] Moldovan President Mircea Snegur admits that the 
Tiraspol leaders could organize various provocations, including 
armed ones, which could lead to bloodshed. This was said in the 
address to the heads of state and governments of Russia, 
Ukraine, and Romania (the members of the quadrilateral group on 
a peaceful settlement of conflicts in Transdniester) and to UN 
Secretary-General Butrus-Ghali published on Wednesday. 
  Snegur pointed out that the socio/political situation in the 
Moldovan left-bank regions had significantly deteriorated. The 
leadership of the Transdniestrian anti-constitutional bodies 
continues to hamper possible settlement of this conflict 
regardless of the efforts to resolve the conflict by peaceful 
political means displayed by Moldova, the Moldovan president 
said. 
  According to the Moldovan leadership, the main goal of the 
Transdniestrian leaders is to prevent the inhabitants of 
Moldova's left-bank regions from participating in the early 
parliamentary elections in Moldova, planned for February 27. 
  Snegur addressed the Russian, Ukrainian, Romanian, and UN 
leaders with a demand to use all their authority and other means 
in order to influence the Tiraspol anti-constitutional bodies 
and to create conditions necessary for normal preparations for 
parliamentary elections. According to the Moldovan president, 
this could be a move forward toward a final settlement of the 
conflict in Transdniester. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

