<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier Notes `Breakthrough' at Davos Forum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0202150894 Tallinn BNS in English 1324 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0202150894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Feb 02, BNS -- Estonian Prime Minister 
Mart Laar attended the World Economic Forum that ended Tuesday 
[1 February] in Davos, Switzerland. The premier was pleased to 
note that Estonia made a breakthrough at the forum. "Estonia was 
all the time spoken about as a real partner," he said. 
  Laar said at a press conference today that economies in 
transition became the focus of attention at the Davos forum. 
"The participants arrived at the conclusion that the transition 
of many states from a planned economy to a market economy makes 
also developed countries undergo major changes," he claimed. 
  The premier said the forum attached great importance to free 
trade and opening of borders as the best ways to develop world 
economy. "The protectionist attitude is considered the greatest 
danger to world economy," he noted. 
  Laar said a high-level Russian delegation arrived in Davos 
to 
convince Western businessmen and politicians that economic 
reforms continue in Russia. "I gathered they didn't succeed very 
well in this," he said. 
  The Estonian premier had several bilateral and three-way 
meetings in Davos. He was pleasantly surprised by the Palestine 
Liberation Organization leader Yasir 'Arafat's high regard for 
Estonia. 
  Laar met in Davos with Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus. 
The two agreed in principle to conclude as soon as possible a 
free-trade agreement between the two countries. 
  The Estonian premier met also with his Swedish and Finnish 
counterparts, Carl Bildt and Esko Aho. Laar said he and Bildt 
had a thorough discussion of the situation in Paldiski. "Sweden 
is prepared to assist Estonia in cleaning up the environment in 
that town," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

