<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegation Meets With Christopher </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202171794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1621 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202171794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Kuchina] </F>
  [Text] Riga February 2 TASS -- Latvia's delegation ended 
talks on Latvian-Russian relations, the withdrawal of Russian 
troops from the republic and the fate of the Russian radar in 
Skrunda in Washington on Wednesday. 
  The delegation met with U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher, Pentagon officials and members of the National 
Security Council. They assured Latvia that no joint tactics of 
troop withdrawal or radar station close-down had been worked out 
during the U.S.-Russian summit meeting in Moscow last month. 
  Their statements ran counter to a NEW YORK TIMES publication 
of January 30, 1994 which said that American and Russian 
specialists had agreed to keep the station for another four 
years and dismantle it within 18 months after that. Latvian 
President Guntis Ulmanis did not rule out the possibility of 
holding a referendum on the radar station. However, Parliament 
Chairman Anatoliy Gorbunovs believes the referendum may disrupt 
negotiations. 
  Latvian parliamentarians who attended the session of the 
Europarliament Inter-parliamentary Assembly in Strasbourg this 
week expressed concern that some influential deputies from 
France, Germany and Britain prioritise the signing of agreements 
between Estonia, Latvia and Russia on troop withdrawal rather 
than the pullout itself. 
  Local observers are at a loss trying to find possible 
explanations to this position. Latvia insists on strict 
observance of resolutions of the United Nations and the 
Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe which call for 
fast and organised withdrawal of troops. At the same time, head 
of the Latvian Parliamentary Commission for Foreign Affairs, 
Aleksandrs Kirsteins, vows that the troops can be withdrawn 
without any agreement. 
  The delegation left the U.S. and flew to Sweden where it 
intends to continue the talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

