<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Delegation Discusses Security </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202201994 Riga Radio Riga Network in Latvian 1800 GMT 2 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0202201994 </F>
<F P=104>  Riga Radio Riga Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Latvian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In the event the Baltic countries or Latvia join the 
Partnership for Peace program and a real danger from Russia 
threatens its security, NATO will not only have consultations 
with the Baltic countries but will try to influence Russia to 
cease its aggressive activity, the delegation of the Latvian 
Defense Ministry was told today in Brussels by (Dick Zandie), 
spokesmen for the political affairs department. 
  (Zandie) added that there are virtually no such threats from 
Russia in reality, and that much would be done for Latvia's 
security by Russia's participation in the Partnership for Peace 
program. In (Zandie's) view, cooperation with Russia would also 
be good for NATO. At NATO headquarters today, the Latvian 
Defense Ministry delegation met with two other NATO spokesmen. 
During the meeting they mainly discussed European security 
problems and the involvement of NATO in solving them. 

</TEXT>

