<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Draft on Russian 1940 Annexation Approved </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0202190194 Tallinn BNS in English 1652 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0202190194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Feb 02, BNS -- The Latvian Saeima 
(parliament) Foreign Affairs' Committee approved the historic 
motivation of a draft document on the occupation and annexation 
of Latvia by the Soviet Union in 1940. 
  The Saeima decided Jan. 27 that this document should be 
submitted to the United Nations together with a request to 
officially recognize that Latvia was occupied in 1940. 
  The adoption of the document does not solve the Russian 
troop 
withdrawal problem but it is still important as an instrument to 
press on Russia, said Indulis Berzins, of the Latvia's Way. 
  If the United Nations approves of the document, Latvia would 
become aware of the attitude of the world community toward the 
occupation, Berzins said. 
  The United Nations, however, may reject or ignore the 
statement if Latvia has not duly prepared its presentation, said 
Janis Jurkans, another speaker at the committee meeting. 
  Democratic Party's Ilga Grava suggested that Lithuanian and 
Estonian parliaments should be invited to draft a common 
statement on occupation. 
  The preliminary coordination of that declaration could take 
place during the Baltic-Nordic seminar, scheduled for Feb. 4-5 
in Riga. 
  Estonia has prepared a similar statement. 
  The committee wants to consult Russian parliamentarians to 
clarify Russia's official stance on the acknowledgement of 
Latvia's occupation. 
  The Foreign Affairs Committee will also contact the Latvian 
envoy to the United Nations, Aivars Baumanis, to find out the 
anticipated reaction of this international organization to the 
Latvian application. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

