<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   1994 Budget Faces Shortfall of 40 Million Lats </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0202143494 Tallinn BNS in English 1110 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0202143494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Feb 02, BNS -- The 1994 budget will fall 40 
million lats short in 1994, State Reforms Minister Maris Gailis 
told reporters Tuesday following a Cabinet meeting. 
  The government will supplement the budget incomes with 30 
million lats of Bank of Latvia's profit payments and cut the 
administrative reform's fund by 1.2 million lats, Gailis said. 
  The group also confirmed a plan to form a working party for 
free trade talks with the European Union and passed for Saeima 
[parliament] consideration a bill on Latvia's signature to 
international labor conventions. 
  The Cabinet failed to accept a resolution on social 
guarantees for parentless children and regulations on easier 
public transportation tariffs to certain categories of 
residents, said government spokesman Sergei Ancupov. 

</TEXT>

