<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials, Groups Preview Yeltsin Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Abkhaz Government Anticipates Visit </H4>
<F P=102> LD0202134994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1224 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tengiz Pachkoria] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi February 2 Tass -- The government-in-exile 
of the Abkhazian Autonomous Republic "pins great hopes on Russia 
for restoring justice: the restoration of the territorial 
integrity of the Georgian state", the Abkhazian government, 
temporarily operating in Tbilisi, issued a statement on 
Wednesday. 
  The statement notes that "the earliest organised return of 
refugees to their homes in Abkhazia without any preliminary 
conditions and restrictions is among the main issues for 
restoring mutual trust between Georgia and Russia". 
  The government asks the Russian leadership "to declare 
unequivocally its negative attitude to statements by the Gudauta 
leaders on the establishment of an independent Abkhazian state 
or its accession to Russia". 
  The government "hopes that the visit by President Boris 
Yeltsin to Tbilisi, the signing of a package of documents and 
planned measures will help to achieve a large-scale settlement 
in Abkhazia, unity and integrity of Georgia in the interests of 
its multinational population as well as to ensure stability and 
peace in the Caucasus as a whole, in Russia and throughout the 
world". 

</TEXT>

