<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seeks Agreement on Russian Bases </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202141094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1203 
GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0202141094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi, 2 Feb -- Pavel Grachev, the Russian defense 
minister, arrived in Tbilisi today. His visit is taking place 
within the framework of the visit by the president of the 
Russian Federation, which starts tomorrow. 
  The key military question to be decided during the Russian 
president's visit is the question of establishing Russian 
military bases on Georgian territory, Pavel Grachev told 
journalists on arrival. 
  The interim agreement on the status of Russian forces in 
Georgia expires in 1995, he recalled. "We are willing to keep 
our troops in Georgia provided military bases are established 
for them. This fits in with the CIS's treaty on collective 
security. If the two heads of state resolve the bases issue 
satisfactorily tomorrow, the agreement will be worked out by 
military experts," the minister said. There is a possibility 
that a protocol of intent on the establishment of Russian 
military bases in Georgia could be signed, he added. 
  If agreement is reached on the bases, the Russian side 
expects to have three military bases on Georgian territory, 
making a total of five in the Transcaucasus area, with a 
combined strength of about 23,000 men. The main task of this 
grouping, Pavel Grachev said, is to safeguard security in the 
Transcaucasus and North Caucasus regions against outside 
threats, within the framework of the CIS's collective treaty. 
  Pavel Grachev also noted that the question of assisting 
Georgia with the formation of an army "would be resolved 
provided political stability is established in the republic, and 
the political status of Abkhazia and South Ossetia defined". 
Pavel Grachev considers it possible that Russian peacekeeping 
forces might be used to settle the situation in Abkhazia, 
provided that both the Georgian and Abkhaz sides ask for this. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

