<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Summit Begins </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302101294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0943 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302101294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi February 3 TASS -- Russo-Georgian summit 
talks began at the Georgian Government House here on Thursday 
morning. The heads of the two states -- Boris Yeltsin and Eduard 
Shevardnadze -- are now having tete-a-tete talks. 
  Members of the two official delegations are meeting at the 
same time behind closed doors in order to make the negotiations 
more comprehensive and constructive. 
  ITAR-TASS has learned that bilateral, primarily economic 
relations between the two countries are now being discussed by 
First Vice-Chairman of the Russian council of Ministers Oleg 
Soskovets and Chairman of the Georgian Cabinet of Ministers Otar 
Patsatsia. 
  Political aspects of inter-state cooperation are being 
discussed by Foreign Ministers Andrey Kozyrev and Aleksandr 
Chikvaydze. Taking part in the talks from the Georgian side is 
Chairman of the Provisional Committee for the Emergency 
Situation in the Republic Jaba Ioseliani and Head of the Human 
Rights and Inter-Ethnic Relations Committee Aleksandr Kavsadze. 
  Judging by the participants of this part of the 
negotiations, 
they are dealing not only with Russo-Georgian relations as a 
whole, but also with some aspects of the Abkhazian and South 
Ossetian problems, as well as with the rights of non-indigenous 
nationalities, particularly the Russian-speaking population. 
  Heads of the defence establishments of the two countries are 
discussing a package of draft documents on cooperation in the 
military sphere. Future military-political cooperation between 
Russia and Georgia depends on the stabilisation of the 
socio-political situation in the republic. This was stated by 
Russian Defence Minister Pavel Grachev on the eve of President 
Yeltsin's visit to Georgia. In his opinion, this also depends 
on the settlement of problems linked with the political statuses 
of Abkhazia and South Ossetia, as well as on Georgia's readiness 
to act in keeping with the Collective Security Treaty. 
  Then the talks were continued on a broader scale with the 
participation of the official delegations of the two countries. 
A package of bilateral Russo-Georgian documents are expected to 
be signed after them. The most important document, of course, 
is the Treaty on Friendship, Good-Neighbourly Relations, and 
Cooperation. 
  ITAR-TASS has learned from circles close to the Georgian 
delegation that the republic's leadership believes that "the 
signing of this treaty will restore the disrupted ancient ties, 
will add new substance to bilateral relations, fully meeting the 
interests of the two nations". 
  A joint press conference will be held by President Yeltsin 
and Eduard Shevardnadze after the signing ceremony. President 
Yeltsin will meet Catholicos-Patriarch of All Georgia Iliya II 
in the second half of the day. Then the Russian president and 
Eduard Shevardnadze will meet Georgian intellectuals. 
  An official dinner will be given in honour of the Russian 
president in the evening of the same day on behalf of head of 
the Georgian state Eduard Shevardnadze. 
  President Yeltsin will return to Moscow late on Thursday 
evening. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

