<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chubays: Government Weakened by Resignations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202164994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1627 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow February 2 TASS -- The resignation of Yegor 
Gaydar, Boris Fedorov and Ella Pamfilova has considerably 
weakened the government, Russian Vice-Prime Minister Anatoliy 
Chubays said. 
  Speaking at a news conference in Moscow on Wednesday, 
Chubays 
said that "there is a threat to the course of reform, although a 
potential one." "There is not a single decision of the 
government which could be regarded as a move to slow down or 
stop reforms," he said. 
  Chubays stressed that the government will adopt a budget for 
the first quarter of the year shortly. "Only after that will we 
be able to understand whether the government is ready to 
continue the course of reform which was pursued in 1993. It 
will also become clear whether the government will continue the 
programme adopted in September 1993," he said. 
  "Only after that can one give a final assessment of the 
government reshuffle," the vice-premier said. 
  Speaking about his plans for the future, Chubays said that 
he 
"intends to bear responsibility for the course of privatisation 
to the end." "The programme of privatisation continues to 
develop. According to our programme, bigger and more efficient 
enterprises will be put on auction in February, March and 
April," he added. 
  Chubays expressed the confidence that the "programme of 
privatisation will be implemented in full and within the terms 
envisaged by the presidential decree." 

</TEXT>

