<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Minister Barannikov Released From Jail </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202160994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1458 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202160994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 2 TASS -- Viktor Barannikov, former 
security minister who was arrested on charges of organising the 
armed opposition revolt last October 3-4 in Moscow, was released 
from jail because of health reasons, according to a decision 
adopted on Wednesday by Prosecutor General Aleksey Kazannik. 
  The press service of the prosecutor's office said that 
Kazannik had adopted the decision after acquainting himself with 
a medical statement which said that Barannikov "needs a special 
medical examination in hospital to decide on the necessity of 
surgical treatment which makes it impossible for him to remain 
in an investigation prison". 
  Barannikov was released on conditions that he does not leave 
Moscow. 
  Barannikov's lawyer had several times complained that his 
client was suffering from heart problems. 
  In January Barannikov was transferred from prison to a 
specially guarded hospital and his lawyer demanded that he be 
placed under house arrest. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-36157 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov023_b_94015" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-023 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chubays Views Current Economic, Political Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202175494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1610 
GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0202175494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 2 Feb -- Anatoliy Chubays regards it as 
unthinkable to freeze the prices of raw materials and energy 
sources, since that would, in his view, lead to huge state 
subsidies for the fuel and energy complex. Answering 
journalists' questions during a news conference, the vice 
premier declared that that proposal, which is contained in a 
report drawn up by academicians Leonid Abalkin, Nikolay 
Petrakov, and Stanislav Shatalin, was dictated by nothing more 
than political expediency. "I don't think there is anything in 
the document that merits serious government discussion," he 
added. 
  Anatoliy Chubays also stated that economists (meaning the 
leaders of the Russian Central Bank) who seriously propose that 
a fixed exchange rate should be set for the ruble "are not 
suitable for responsible work in the Russian leadership." 
  Speaking of the balance of forces within the reformed 
Russian 
government, Anatoliy Chubays described it as "very difficult." 
But the positions of these forces, he continued, "are not set 
for all time to come." "The very fact that Fedorov and Gaydar 
have moved on has already brought about a situation in which the 
arduous and thankless function that they performed will be taken 
on by other members of the government. So I would not be in a 
hurry to state that the reformers in the government have 
suffered a complete reverse and that they have no resources 
left," the vice premier stressed. 
  Anatoliy Chubays announced that he has no plans to leave the 
present Russian government. "My plans are to do everything 
possible to see that the government conducts the reform policy 
for which I have worked within it for the past two years." 
  He also said that he has "good, working" relations with 
Viktor Chernomyrdin and First Vice Premier Oleg Soskovets. 
Anatoliy Chubays added that he can find a common position with 
them, even though there are differences of approach. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

