<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Budget Expenses Close to 61 Trillion Rubles in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102172194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1620 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102172194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By BUSINESS-TASS] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 1 TASS -- Russian budget expenses in 
1993 were close to 61 trillion roubles and comprised 37.8 per 
cent of the gross national product, according to the Finance 
Ministry. 
  The figure for 1992 equalled 33 per cent and the 1993 
increase was caused mostly by the budget article called "Other 
Expenses" which the ministry did not specify in its report on 
Tuesday. 
  The "other expenses" grew from 13.4 per cent in 1992 to 21.4 
per cent in 1993. 
  Defence expenses dropped from 14.3 to 12.4 per cent. 
  Although the major share of appropriations goes to the 
national economy, it decreased from 34.5 to 27.3 per cent. 
  More money was allocated to "social and cultural measures" - 
23.1 per cent in 1992 and 24.9 per cent in 1993. 
  Approrpiations for science, police, governing and 
controlling 
bodies, as well as for foreign economic activities varied from 
1.6 to 5.1 per cent in 1993. 
  Finance Ministry experts said that budget spendings 
increased 
because of credits for grain purchases in Russia, for conversion 
and loans to CIS states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

