<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Oppose Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0202180594 Moscow SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA in Russian 3 Feb 94 p 
5 </F>

<F P=103> PM0202180594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Nadezhda Garifullina: "Caucasus United Prior to </F>
President's Visit to Georgia"] 
  [Text] B. Yeltsin's visit to Tbilisi and the forthcoming 
signing of the treaty between Georgia and Russia have become the 
subject of discussion at the meeting in the Foreign Ministry 
between A. Kozyrev and leaders of the North Caucasus republics. 
They expressed their critical attitude toward the draft treaty. 
Meeting with some of the participants in the meeting, our 
correspondent asked them to explain their position. 
  Akhsarbek Galazov, president of the Republic of North 
Ossetia: 
  "I believe that Russia should not sign any treaty with 
Georgia until there is a political settlement of the problem of 
Abkhazia and South Ossetia. If a treaty is signed clearly 
determining the fate of these two republics and they finally 
receive a political settlement of their problems -- I am wholly 
in favor. 
  "I believe that South Ossetia should be recognized as a 
republic and that through the joint efforts of Georgia and 
Russia an economic basis should be placed under that decision, 
that the regions which were in fact seized should be returned to 
South Ossetia and all refugees should return. 
  "Second, and that is perhaps the main thing, we are also in 
favor of Georgia's integrity. But it will not be preserved as a 
single state unless the Georgian people's leaders realize that 
they must consider realities. After all, in fact Abkhazia and 
South Ossetia are now outside Georgia. To ensure that they are 
part of Georgia they must sit down with them at the conference 
table, sign a treaty, and satisfy their peoples' demands to the 
maximum. 
  "All questions existing today in the North Caucasus cannot 
be 
examined only within that region. The Caucasus is united and 
its division into the North Caucasus and the Transcaucasus seems 
to me utterly artificial. At the meeting at the Foreign 
Ministry there were statements in which Georgia was called the 
aggressor, with whom a treaty cannot be signed. And indeed, it 
did after all in fact perpetrate aggression. Seeking to drive 
non-Georgians out of South Ossetia, Georgia seized the territory 
of what was then still an autonomous oblast. 
  "As for Abkhazia it was artificially joined to Georgia back 
in Soviet times and Georgia also perpetrated aggression against 
Abkhazia using the national extremists' forces. And we believe 
that today Russia should not sign a wide-ranging treaty with 
Georgia. The problems of Abkhazia and South Ossetia are 
closely, directly linked with Russia. Nearly all the North 
Caucasus republics, krays, and oblasts took part in the defense 
of Abkhazia. And what happened in Abkhazia has found a response 
in Adygeya, Karachayevo-Cherkesiya, Krasnodar and Stavropol 
krays, and Kabardino-Balkariya.... 
  "And surely South Ossetia's troubles cannot be viewed in 
isolation from North Ossetia? Any shot in the south echoes in 
North Ossetia. For the fourth year now not a single kilogram of 
food, not a single tablet or tube of medicine has reached South 
Ossetia from Georgia, nor have necessities been arriving. South 
Ossetia is supplied via North Ossetia and is in fact maintained 
by Russia. So surely Russia cannot sign a treaty until the 
problems of Abkhazia and South Ossetia are settled?" 
  Magomedali Magomedov, chairman of the Republic of Dagestan 
Supreme Soviet: 
  "Before discussing the draft treaty we were not familiarized 
with it in advance. I believe that as a whole the treaty is 
aimed at establishing normal mutual relations between Russia and 
Georgia. But we are worried by the position of South Ossetia 
and Abkhazia and we said that agreements with the Georgian 
leadership should be reached on these issues, that is these 
questions should not be bypassed when concluding a treaty". 
  Vladimir Khubiyev, chairman of the Karachayevo-Cherkess 
Republic Council of Ministers: 
  "I think that reason will nonetheless triumph and a 
political 
solution will be found for ensuring these republics' peaceful 
coexistence and the rights of each republic should be as they 
are determined by the peoples themselves -- of Abkhazia, South 
Ossetia, and Georgia. Now is not the time when someone can be 
switched to someone else's subordination and when a big nation 
can dictate its will to a small people. I know the opinion of 
the Abkhazians -- both the ordinary citizens and the leaders. 
They all, down to the last person, favor independence. In what 
form is another question." 

</TEXT>

