<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Denies Kurils To Be No-Entry Zone </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202131894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1215 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Yevgeniy Belovitskiy] </F>
  [Text] Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk February 2 TASS -- Reports that 
the Sakhalin governor intends to make the south Kuril Islands a 
no-entry zone, which were run by a number of the Japanese media 
last week, were disproved by Vitaliy Dubov, acting head of a 
department of the Sakhalin administration. He said these 
reports meant sensation-seeking and attempts to pass "white for 
black". 
  Chiefs of the administration now draft a resolution 
connected 
with the Russian law on the state border. Jurists consider the 
proposal to allocate in a number of districts of the Sakhalin 
region five kilometre frontier belts with special regulations 
for the stay of Russian and foreign citizens, but not the 
prohibition of their stay. 
  It is yet early to dwell on specific features of the 
document. One thing is certain: it will be fully in keeping with 
the law on the Russian border. 
  The Sakhalin governor himself favours the freedom of travel 
of citizens in the territory of their country in accordance with 
accepted norms. 

</TEXT>

