<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Adopts Procedural Rules </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202142394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1234 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202142394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Lyudmila Aleksandrova and Anna </F>
Melnikova] 
  [Text] Moscow February 2 TASS -- The Federation Council 
adopted today on the whole the procedural rules of the upper 
chamber, which consist of 13 chapters, as well as a resolution 
on the procedural rules of the first Federation Council. The 
legislators discussed amendments to two out of the three parts 
of the rules, which deal with general procedural regulations of 
holding sessions of the upper chamber, as well as the procedure 
of the discussion of laws adopted by the State Duma. 
  The Editing Commission will submit its remarks concerning 
the 
third part of the procedural rules before March 1. This part 
deals with the discussion of issues, which, in accordance with 
Article 102 of the Constitution, are within the authority of the 
federation Council. These include the approval of the changing 
of borders between subjects of the Russian federation, of 
presidential decrees on imposing martial law, the taking of a 
decision on whether or not Russian troops should be used outside 
the Russian territory, the naming of the date of presidential 
elections, the impeachment of the president and so on. 
  Members of the Federation Council assigned the Committee for 
the Affairs of the Federation, the Federal Treaty and Regional 
Policy to take part in the forthcoming talks in Moscow between 
Russian and Tatarstan on concluding a federal treaty. They 
decided as well to assign the committee to analyse the problem 
of starting negotiations with the Chechen Republic and to report 
the results to the upper chamber. 
  A break until Thursday was announced at the session of the 
Federation Council. The agenda of the Thursday meeting includes 
a government report about its intentions in the sphere of the 
financial, crediting, tax, agrarian and industrial policy. 
Initially it was planned that the report would be made by head 
of the government Viktor Chernomyrdin. Today, however, Chairman 
of the Federation Council Vladimir Shumeyko did not specify 
today who would make the report. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

