<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Urges Parliament To Harmonize Procedural Rules </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202191294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1721 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202191294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature No. 22 for 2 </F>
February 1994; by Andrey Pershin, Andrey Petrovskiy, and 
Vladimir Shishlin, edited by Boris Grishchenko] 
  [Text] President Yeltsin has called on deputies of the 
Federal Assembly to bring the temporary rules of the Federation 
Council and the State Duma in line with the Russian 
Constitution. In compliance with the Constitution, the houses 
of the Federal Assembly pass decisions by a majority vote from 
the total number of members of the Federation Council and 
deputies to the State Duma correspondingly in all cases except 
where the Constitution says otherwise, reads the president's 
address spread on Tuesday in the Russian parliament. 
  When the houses passed the temporary rules, the notion "the 
total number of deputies" was interpreted as the number of 
effectively elected of each of the houses. In line with the 
Constitution, the total number of deputies in the Duma is 450 
and in the Federation Council-- 178, while elected were 444 and 
171 respectively. 
  The interpretation of the notion "total number of deputies" 
as the number of the elected deputies suggests the recognition 
that the houses consist of a different number of deputies than 
that envisaged by the Russian Constitution. Thus the decisions 
of the houses cannot be considered constitutional, believes the 
Russian president. It follows that when the houses adopted their 
provisional rules, deputies violated provisions of Articles 95, 
102 and 103 of the Russian Constitution, said Yeltsin. 
  The presidential message says that the loose interpretation 
of the constitutional norms enables both houses of the Federal 
Assembly in the future to adopt laws and other decisions 
contrary to the requirements of the Russian Constitution. 
  IF Note: In connection with the president's message, 
parliamentary observers note that the speaker of the State Duma 
Ivan Rybkin had received 223 votes in his favor to become 
speaker. This means he was elected by a one vote majority out 
of the number of the elected deputies. The points made by 
Yeltsin virtually call into question the fact that Rybkin was 
elected constitutionally, which, some experts believe, could 
lead to a deterioration in the relationships between the 
president and the Duma. 
  Meanwhile, at the Federation Council session Wednesday, 
deputies turned down the presidential amendments which proposed 
to count votes out of the total number of the Federation Council 
members, not from among those elected. If passed, such a 
decision would have meant the relieving of the chairman of the 
Federation Council and his deputies and the election of members 
of Federation Council committees. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
